equation_narrative.headline: Polar surface context drives serine selection despite early hydrophobic representation
equation_narrative.story: Position 65 in ubiquitin sits in a polar-rich surface environment (NIQKE[S]TLHLV), with 5 structural contacts and minimal co-evolutionary signal. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation that initially appears hydrophobic-leaning (alanine peaks at 34% at L31 in the logit lens), reflecting local sequence patterns. However, this is not a prediction—it's the model encoding the structural context. The decision phase (L24-33) reveals the true constraint: strong serine-specific MLP neurons activate at L27-28, driven by the polar surface environment. Serine emerges decisively at L30 (36%) and wins with 46.6%, while valine (23%) and alanine (7%) remain as hydrophobic alternatives.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a complex representation of position 65's biochemical context. Five structural contacts are read, though attention heads show relatively weak structural focus (L12 head 2 erases with -2.37 projection but only 0.3% structural attention). The logit lens shows volatile shifts—histidine, glutamate, glycine, arginine, and lysine all briefly lead—reflecting the model's encoding of mixed signals: a polar-rich local sequence (N, Q, K, E nearby) but also hydrophobic neighbors (L, V). By L17, alanine rises to 10% and peaks at 34% at L31, indicating the representation has accumulated hydrophobic character from local sequence patterns. However, this is representation character, not prediction. SAE features at L18 show moderate activation (F18:244 at 14.29 projection, F18:5271 at 14.1), suggesting the model is still integrating contextual information rather than committing to a specific amino acid.
perception_phase.context_character: The assembled context by L23 is polar-surface dominant with mixed hydrophobic signals. Local sequence is rich in charged/polar residues (N, I, Q, K, E nearby), with 5 structural contacts providing additional context. The representation shows hydrophobic-leaning character in the logit lens (alanine at 8% at L23), but this reflects the model encoding local sequence patterns rather than a prediction.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 5 residues within 8Å, read weakly by attention heads (L12 H2 shows 0.3% structural attention)
Co-evolutionary signal: minimal (1 co-evolving position detected)
Local sequence: strong polar/charged character (NIQKE context) read by L8 H6 (2.26 projection, 81% local attention)
L18 SAE features: F18:244 (14.29 proj), F18:5271 (14.1 proj) encode intermediate contextual state

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes between L27-30. At L27, serine-specific MLP neurons activate strongly (N27:3518 projects 0.668 to S, N27:311 projects 0.615 to S), pushing serine from 11% to 17%. Layer 28 sees a dramatic surge: threonine briefly peaks at 41.6% (driven by polar-favoring neurons), but this is immediately countered at L29-30. By L30, serine takes the lead at 36%, supported by N30:2285 (1.108 projection to S) and N30:4517 (0.615 projection). Final layers 31-33 consolidate: serine reaches 46.6% while alanine (which peaked at 34% at L31) falls to 7%.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the shift from context encoding to prediction. At L23, the logit lens shows serine at only 5.5% with alanine at 8%, reflecting the hydrophobic-leaning representation character. By L24, SAE features shift to higher specificity (F24:7582 at 26.94 projection), and MLP neurons begin casting amino-acid-specific votes. Layer 25 shows the first clear prediction signal: serine rises to 11% as polar-specific neurons activate (N25:1636 projects 0.446 to S).

candidates.narrative: Serine emerges as the winner through strong MLP support in the decision phase. At L27, serine-specific neurons activate (N27:3518 projects 0.668, N27:311 projects 0.615), pushing serine from 11% to 17%. Layer 28 brings a surge with N28:4646 projecting 0.831 to serine. Despite competition from threonine (which peaks at 41.6% at L28) and alanine (34% at L31), serine takes the lead at L30 (36%) and consolidates to 46.6% by L33. The decisive evidence is the polar surface context: multiple neurons vote for serine based on the NIQKE local environment.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L27, leads from L30, final 46.6%
key_evidence: N27:3518 (MLP, 0.668 proj to S) — serine-specific neuron activates
N28:4646 (MLP, 0.831 proj to S) — strongest serine writer
N30:2285 (MLP, 1.108 proj to S) — consolidates serine lead

candidates.narrative: Valine finishes second at 23.3%, representing the hydrophobic alternative to serine. Valine maintains steady support through the decision phase (4.6% at L23, rising to 23.3% at L33), driven by neurons that favor small hydrophobic residues in surface positions. The late surge (L32-33) suggests the model recognizes valine as a viable alternative given the mixed hydrophobic signals in the local sequence (L, V nearby). However, valine never leads in the decision phase, as the polar context ultimately dominates.
key_evidence: N32:4433 (MLP, -1.43 proj to S, favors I/V) — late hydrophobic push
Maintains presence throughout decision phase despite polar dominance

candidates.narrative: Alanine dominates the logit lens through much of the perception phase, peaking at 34.3% at L31. This reflects the model's encoding of hydrophobic character from local sequence patterns (L, V nearby) and small-residue preferences. However, this is representation character, not prediction. The logit lens projects the intermediate representation through the unembedding head, and alanine's high probability indicates the representation is hydrophobic-leaning. In the decision phase, alanine briefly leads at L12-13 and L15-17, then surges again at L31-32, but ultimately loses to serine as polar-specific neurons activate. Alanine finishes at 7%.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L12-13, L15-17, peaks 34% L31, collapses to 7% L33
key_evidence: Early hydrophobic representation: 20% at L0, 23.7% at L12
Late surge at L31 (34%) reflects residual hydrophobic signal
N31:3767 (MLP, 0.833 proj to S, 0.958 to T) — polar shift erases alanine

candidates.narrative: Threonine, the other polar small residue, briefly dominates at L28 with 41.6%, driven by N28:4279 (which projects -0.628 to S but 0.699 to T). This represents the model's consideration of threonine as a polar alternative to serine. However, threonine's support collapses at L29-30 as serine-specific neurons activate more strongly. Threonine finishes at 6.5%, indicating the model ultimately prefers serine's hydroxyl group over threonine's methyl-hydroxyl combination for this surface position.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks 41.6% at L28, collapses to 6.5% by L33
key_evidence: N28:4279 (MLP, 0.699 proj to T) — brief threonine surge
Loses to serine as N29-30 neurons favor S over T

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from charged (arginine, lysine lead at L7-17) to hydrophobic (alanine takes over at L12). This reflects the model integrating local sequence information: the NIQKE context suggests charged residues, but the nearby L and V push the representation toward hydrophobic character. Multiple lead changes (R→A→R→K→A) indicate the model is still assembling context, not predicting. MLP neurons show mixed signals: N12:1375 writes 0.237 to S, but N12:2133 erases with -0.184 (favoring Q).

The decisive turning point. At L27, serine-specific MLP neurons activate (N27:3518 projects 0.668, N27:311 projects 0.615), pushing serine from 11% to 17%. Layer 28 sees threonine surge to 41.6%, but this is immediately countered at L29-30 as serine neurons consolidate (N30:2285 projects 1.108 to S). Serine takes the lead at L30 (36%) and never relinquishes it. The key velocity event at L27 shows +6.55 total delta (MLP-driven, +4.7 MLP delta), marking the moment the model commits to the polar solution.

Final consolidation and competition resolution. Alanine makes a late surge to 34% at L31 (driven by residual hydrophobic signal), briefly overtaking serine at L32. However, L33 sees a massive shift: N32:4433 erases with -1.43 projection (favoring I/V over S), but serine-writing neurons (N32:2029 at 0.922, N32:4230 at 0.776) overpower this. The final velocity event at L33 shows -17.09 total delta (away from S), but serine still wins at 46.6% because it had built sufficient lead. Valine surges to 23.3% as the hydrophobic runner-up.

deep_dives.label: Early attention L8-12
deep_dives.caption: L8 H6 writes 2.26 projection with 81% local attention, reading the NIQKE polar context. L12 H2 erases with -2.37 projection but shows weak structural focus (0.3% structural attention), suggesting it's suppressing early charged signals rather than reading structural contacts.

deep_dives.label: SAE features L9-18
deep_dives.caption: L9 features show high activation (F9:5728 at 55.88, F9:1281 at 51.2), encoding the local sequence context. By L18, activation drops (F18:244 at 14.29, F18:5271 at 14.1), indicating the representation is transitioning from context encoding to prediction preparation.

deep_dives.label: Decision transition L23-25
deep_dives.caption: L24 marks the shift to prediction mode. F24:7582 (26.94 proj) and F24:4430 (19.9 proj) show higher specificity than earlier features, indicating amino-acid-specific prediction channels are activating. The logit lens shows serine rising from 5.5% (L23) to 7.8% (L24).

deep_dives.label: MLP surge L27-28
deep_dives.caption: The decisive serine push. L27 activates N27:3518 (0.668 proj to S) and N27:311 (0.615 proj to S). L28 brings N28:4646 (0.831 proj to S) and N28:2372 (0.716 proj to S). These neurons recognize the polar surface context and vote strongly for serine. Threonine briefly peaks at L28 (41.6%) but loses as serine neurons consolidate.

deep_dives.label: MLP consolidation L29-30
deep_dives.caption: Serine consolidates its lead. N29:493 (0.669 proj to S) and N29:1742 (0.618 proj to S) maintain momentum. L30 brings N30:2285 (1.108 proj to S, strongest single neuron) and N30:4517 (0.615 proj to S). Serine takes the lead at 36% and never relinquishes it.

deep_dives.label: Final competition L31-33
deep_dives.caption: Alanine makes a late surge (34% at L31) driven by N31:3767, but serine writers (N32:2029 at 0.922, N32:4230 at 0.776) overpower it. N32:4433 erases with -1.43 projection (favoring I/V), allowing valine to surge to 23.3% as runner-up. Despite the L33 velocity event (-17.09 delta away from S), serine's accumulated lead ensures victory at 46.6%.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts serine by recognizing position 65's polar surface context. Through layers 1-23, the representation shows hydrophobic-leaning character (alanine peaks at 34% in the logit lens), reflecting the model's encoding of local sequence patterns with mixed signals. However, in the decision phase (L24-33), serine-specific MLP neurons activate strongly at L27-30, driven by the NIQKE polar-rich environment. The strongest evidence is the coordinated activation of serine writers: N27:3518 (0.668), N28:4646 (0.831), and N30:2285 (1.108). Despite late competition from alanine (34% at L31) and valine (23.3% final), serine's polar character matches the surface context, yielding a confident 46.6% prediction.
